The case involves **Stephen Chan Chi Wan** (General Manager (Broadcasting) at TVB) and **Tseng Pei Kun** (director of IEAP, Chan’s agent for external engagements). Chan hosted a popular TVB talk show *“Be My Guest”* (not part of his contractual duties) and occasionally did paid external events via IEAP. Olympian City (OC), a shopping mall, sponsored TVB’s 2009 New Year’s Eve Countdown show and wanted to add a live *“Be My Guest”* segment with Chan interviewing Lai Yiu Cheung. OC contracted IEAP to secure Chan’s appearance, paying IEAP $160,000—IEAP retained $28,000, paying $112,000 to Chan and $20,000 to Lai. Chan did not seek TVB’s written approval for the external work (contractually required) but TVB knew he was involved.  

The prosecution charged them with: (1) conspiracy to commit an agent-acceptance offense under POBO §9(1)(a); (2) Chan accepting an advantage (§9(1)(a)); (3) Tseng offering an advantage (§9(2)(a)). The trial judge acquitted, but the Court of Appeal (CA) twice reversed the acquittal, convicting on the conspiracy charge. The Court of Final Appeal (CFA) allowed the appeals, quashing all convictions.  


